pgTitle: Matches of the Republic of Ireland national football team

rows.text: Football Association of the Irish Free State
Team name changed from "Irish Free State" to "Ireland".
First international match held in Cork.
England's first home defeat by non-British side. Crowd: 51,047.
FIFA renamed team from "Ireland" to "Republic of Ireland".
Ireland was first team ever eliminated from European Nations' Cup. Crowd: 41,691.
European Nations' Cup name changed to European Football Championship.
Abandoned at 51 minutes because of fog. Replayed 1969-10-15.
Unofficial match. First win since 1967 (four years).
Rio de Janeiro, Estádio do Maracanã
First official international match against Northern Ireland.
Ireland eliminated by France on goal difference.
This match recognised as an official international match.
Unofficial match. Ireland's first appearance in the final of an international football competition.
Ireland won their first international tournament. Crowd: 1,000.
First Irish appearance at European Championship tournament. Crowd: 51,573.
Crowd: 60,800. Eliminated team welcomed home by 200,000 people.
First Irish appearance at World Cup finals tournament.
Promoted to second round via 3 draws, 2 goals.
Final international match at Dalymount Park.
Unbeaten, yet failed to qualify for Euro 1992.
European Championship became known as Euro.
First World Cup match where Ireland scored more than one goal.
After extra time: 1–1. Penalty shoot out: Ireland 2–3 Spain.
Competition between three countries with large communities in London. Crowd: 7,438.
Worst home result since May 1966 (40 years).
First match in Croke Park. Crowd: 72,539.
Manager: Don Givens. Crowd: 24,619. Millennium Stadium one-third full.
New manager: Giovanni Trapattoni. Unofficial match. Training match only.
Unofficial match. Republic of Ireland XI. Crowd: 4,040.
Re-built Thomond Park has a capacity of 26,000. Crowd: 19,428.
Final match played at Croke Park. Highest domestic attendance: 74,103.
Friendly. Ireland hosted and won the tournament. Crowd: 19,783.
World Champions defeated by Irish B team. Crowd: 21,516.
Ireland qualified for Euro 2012 tournament. Crowd: 51,151.
Ireland unbeaten in 14 matches. Match delayed 20 minutes by thunderstorm.
Ireland's first match at a major tournament since World Cup 2002. Croatia was the first team ever to score in the first five minutes of each half at the European Championships. Crowd: 39,550.
Crowd:80,126. Part of the English FA's 150th anniversary celebrations.
500th official match. Manager: Noel King. Crowd: 46,237.
